===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|remembren}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|remembrer||to remember}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|rememorari||to remember again}}, from {{m|la|re-}} + {{m|la|memor||mindful}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*mer-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*(s)mer-||to think about, be mindful, remember}}. Cognate with {{cog|ang|mimorian}}, {{m|ang|mymerian||to remember, commemorate}}, {{cog|ang|māmorian||to deliberate, plan out, design}}. More at {{l|en|mammer}}.

{{rel-top|etymology note}}
The success of the [[Old French]] word was aided by its proximity in sound and meaning to an existing {{etyl|gem|en}} word: {{cog|ang|mimorian}}, {{m|ang|mymerian}} "to remember, commemorate" from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*mimrōną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*mīmrōną||to remember, be mindful}}, from the same {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} source, and is akin to {{etyl|stq|-}} ''[[mimerje|mīmerje]]'' "to ponder, reflect", {{etyl|gml|-}} ''[[mimeren|mīmeren, mīmern]]'' "to ponder, meditate", {{etyl|dum|-}} ''[[mimeren#Middle Dutch|mīmeren]]'' "to reflect, think to oneself" ({{cog|nl|mijmeren||to muse, reflect deeply}}), [[Old English]] {{m|ang|mimor||mindful}}, {{etyl|non|-}} ''[[Mímir]]'', ''[[Mim]]'', Norse god of Memory, [[Old English]] ''[[mamrian#Old English|māmrian]]'' "to think out, design". Related to {{l|en|mourn}}.

Displaced native {{cog|enm|ȝemuneȝen||to remember|sc=Latinx}}, from {{cog|ang|ġemynegian||to remember, remind}}; {{cog|enm|minnen||to remember, have in mind}}, from {{cog|non|minna||to remind}}; {{cog|enm|munden}}, {{m|enm|ȝemunden||to bear in mind, remember|sc=Latinx}}, from {{cog|ang|ġemynd||memory, remembrance}}; {{cog|enm|ithenchen}}, {{m|enm|ȝethenchen||to think on, remember|sc=Latinx}}, from {{cog|ang|ġeþencan}}; {{cog|enm|manien||to remind, mention, remember}}, from {{cog|ang|manian||to admonish, remind, mention}}.
{{rel-bottom}}

